	<text>
		<body>
			<div type="letter" decls="#peltong_01">
				<pb n="1"/>
				<opener>
					<dateline>
						<placeName key="Fort Lesley J. McNair, Washington, DC" ref="https://geohack.toolforge.org/geohack.php?params=38_52_1_N_77_0_57_W">Washington D.C.</placeName>
						<date when="1918-06-04">June 4th, 1918.</date>
					</dateline>
					<address>
						<addrLine>Mr. Earl R. Silvers</addrLine>
						<addrLine><placeName key="Rutgers College, New Brunswick, NJ" ref="https://tools.wmflabs.org/geohack/geohack.php?params=40_30_2_N_74_26_50_W">Rutgers College</placeName></addrLine>
						<addrLine>New Brunswick, N.J.</addrLine>
					</address>
					<salute>My dear Mr. <persName key="Silvers, Earl Reed" from="1891" to="1948" role="Director, War Service Bureau" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/68516378">Silvers</persName>:—</salute>
				</opener>

				<p>
					I should appreciate it very much if you would forward me the names and addresses
					of such Rutgers men that you know are in the military or naval service in the
					vicinity of Washington.
				</p>
				<p>
					I am attached at present to the <orgName>Personnel Office of the 1st Replacement
					<choice><abbr>Regt.</abbr><expan>Regiment</expan></choice> of Engineers</orgName>–
				</p>

				<closer>
					<salute>Very sincerely yours,</salute><lb/>
					<signed><persName key="Pelton, Graham" from="1895" to="1981" role="Private, Engineers">Graham Pelton</persName> '18</signed><lb/>
					<address>
						<addrLine>Room # 209 <choice><abbr>Hdqtes.</abbr><expan>Headquarters</expan></choice> Bldg.</addrLine>
						<addrLine><seg xml:id="fn1">Washington Barracks</seg><note type="gloss" target="#fn1"><p>The Washington Barracks were located at present-day Fort Lesley J. McNair. This was also the site of the Army Engineer School at the time.</p></note><ref target="https://planning.dc.gov/sites/default/files/dc/sites/op/publication/attachments/Fort%20Leslie%20J%20%20McNair%20nomination.pdf">National Park Service, National Register of Historic Places Inventory -- Nomination Form, p. 8.</ref>,</addrLine>
						<addrLine>Washington D.C.</addrLine>
					</address>
				</closer>
			</div>
			<div type="letter" decls="#peltong_02">
				<pb n="2"/>
				<opener>
					<address>
						<addrLine>Room 209 <choice><abbr>Hdqtes</abbr><expan>Headquarters</expan></choice> Bldg.</addrLine>
						<addrLine><placeName key="Fort Lesley J. McNair, Washington, DC" ref="https://geohack.toolforge.org/geohack.php?params=38_52_1_N_77_0_57_W">Washington Bks. D.C.</placeName></addrLine>
					</address>
					<dateline>
						<date when="1918-08-17">August 17th 1918</date>.
					</dateline>
					<address>
						<addrLine>Earl Reed Silvers,</addrLine>
						<addrLine>Rutgers College,</addrLine>
						<addrLine>New Brunswick, N.J.</addrLine>
					</address>
					<salute>My dear Mr. <persName key="Silvers, Earl Reed" from="1891" to="1948" role="Director, War Service Bureau" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/68516378">Silvers</persName> —</salute>
				</opener>

				<p>
					The monthly War Service letters
					have been arriving regularly, and they
					certainly are a great institution. When one
					reads of the important part Rutgers men
					are taking in world events, the ivy covered
					walls of <placeName key="Old Queens, New Brunswick, NJ" ref="https://geohack.toolforge.org/geohack.php?params=40_29_55.5_N_74_26_46.5_W">old Queens</placeName> form a mental image
					dear to his heart.
				</p>
				<p>
				While uptown recently, I ran across
					<choice><abbr>Lieut.</abbr><expan>Lieutenant</expan></choice> <persName key="Stang, William Henry" from="1894" to="1973" role="Lieutenant, Engineers" ref="https://doi.org/doi:10.7282/T3BK1G6X">"Bill" Stang</persName> '16. He was on his way to <placeName key="Camp Forrest, Fort Oglethorpe, GA" ref="https://geohack.toolforge.org/geohack.php?params=34_56_58.75_N_85_15_10.66_W">Camp Forrest, Ga.</placeName>, a new Engineers camp.</p>

				<closer>
					<salute>Yours for success</salute><lb/>
					<signed><persName key="Pelton, Graham" from="1895" to="1981" role="Private, Engineers">Graham Pelton</persName> Ex '18.</signed>
				</closer>
			</div>

			<div type="letter" decls="#peltong_03">
				<pb n="3"/>
				<note type="letterhead">
					<address>
						<addrLine>PERSONNEL OFFICE</addrLine>
						<addrLine>HEADQUARTERS FIRST REPLACEMENT REGIMENT OF ENGINEERS</addrLine>
						<addrLine><placeName key="Fort Lesley J. McNair, Washington, DC" ref="https://geohack.toolforge.org/geohack.php?params=38_52_1_N_77_0_57_W">WASHINGTON BARRACKS, D.C.</placeName></addrLine>
					</address>
				</note>
				<opener>
					<dateline>
						<date when="1918-08-26">August, 26th, 1918.</date>
					</dateline>
					<address>
						<addrLine>Mr. Earl Reed Silvers,</addrLine>
						<addrLine>Rutgers College,</addrLine>
						<addrLine>New Brunswick, New Jersey.</addrLine>
					</address>
					<salute>My dear Mr. <persName key="Silvers, Earl Reed" from="1891" to="1948" role="Director, War Service Bureau" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/68516378">Silvers</persName>:-</salute>
				</opener>

				<p>
					I dislike to cause you unnecessary trouble,
					but I should appreciate it very much if you were to mail me a
					list of Rutgers men who are commissioned in any branch of the
					Engineers, <seg xml:id="fn2">Ordnance</seg><note type="gloss" target="#fn2"><quote>A branch of the armed forces dealing with the supply and storage of weapons, ammunition, and related equipment</quote><ref>New Oxford American Dictionary</ref></note>, Aircraft Production or Quartermaster Corps,
					with their addresses so far as known.
				</p>
				<p>
					<sic>Some one</sic> came up to my desk the other afternoon
					and said he would like to see me for a few minutes. It
					proved to be Mr. <persName key="Klein, Harry R." from="1893" to-iso="19--" role="Unknown" ref="https://doi.org/doi:10.7282/T3W66PJZ">Kline</persName> who graduated in the class of 1917. He
					was on his way to the Engineer Officers Training Camp at <placeName key="Camp Belvoir, VA" ref="https://geohack.toolforge.org/geohack.php?params=38.719737_N_77.154582_W">Camp <choice><sic>Humphries</sic><corr>Humphreys</corr></choice>, Va.</placeName>
				</p>
				<p>
					Received the new <seg xml:id="fn3">War Letter</seg><note type="annotation" target="#fn3"><p>Silvers sent a biweekly letter to Rutgers men in service with news of Rutgers sports and other doings on campus.</p><ref target="https://sinclairnj.blogs.rutgers.edu/2018/03/rutgers-in-the-first-world-war-march-1918-everybody-is-in-the-war/">Radick, C. Rutgers in the First World War, March 1918---'Everybody is in the War.'</ref></note> last week, and
					it was extremely interesting.
				</p>
				<closer>
					<salute>Yours,</salute><lb/>
					<signed><persName key="Pelton, Graham" from="1895" to="1981" role="Private, Engineers">Graham Pelton</persName>, Class 1918.</signed><lb/>
					<address>
						<addrLine>Room 209. Headquarters Bldg.</addrLine>
					</address>
				</closer>
			</div>
			<div type="letter" decls="#peltong_04">
				<pb n="4"/>
				<opener>
					<dateline>
						<date when="1918-08-27">August 27th, 1918.</date>
					</dateline>
					<address>
						<addrLine>Mr. Graham Pelton,</addrLine>
						<addrLine>Room 209, Headquarters Bldg.</addrLine>
						<addrLine><placeName key="Fort Lesley J. McNair, Washington, DC" ref="https://geohack.toolforge.org/geohack.php?params=38_52_1_N_77_0_57_W">Washington Barracks, D.C.</placeName></addrLine>
					</address>
					<salute>Dear Mr. <persName key="Pelton, Graham" from="1895" to="1981" role="Private, Engineers">Pelton</persName>:</salute>
				</opener>

				<p>
					I am sorry that I am not able to send you the
					list of commissioned officers as suggested in your letter of
					August 26th. We have not such a list in type at the present
					time. We are short of clerical help just now and it is not
					possible for us to give the time to such work.
				</p>
				<p>
					I thank you for your interest and wish you success
					in the line of work you have undertaken.
				</p>

				<closer>
					<salute>Very truly yours,</salute><lb/>
					<signed><persName key="Silvers, Earl Reed" from="1891" to="1948" role="Director, War Service Bureau" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/68516378"></persName><lb/>
					<subst><del>R</del><add>D</add></subst>irector.</signed>
					<signed>ERS/H</signed>
				</closer>
			</div>
			<div type="letter" decls="#peltong_05">
				<pb n="5"/>
				<note type="letterhead">
					<address>
						<addrLine>ENGINEER SCHOOL</addrLine>
						<addrLine>UNITED STATES ARMY</addrLine>
						<addrLine><placeName key="Fort Lesley J. McNair, Washington, DC">WASHINGTON BARRACKS, D.C.</placeName></addrLine>
					</address>
				</note>
				<opener>
					<dateline>
						<date when="1918-11-02">November 2, 1918.</date>
					</dateline>
					<address>
						<addrLine>Mr. Earl R. Silvers,</addrLine>
						<addrLine><placeName key="Rutgers College, New Brunswick, NJ" ref="https://tools.wmflabs.org/geohack/geohack.php?params=40_30_2_N_74_26_50_W">Rutgers College</placeName>,</addrLine>
						<addrLine>New Brunswick, New Jersey.</addrLine>
					</address>
					<salute>Dear Mr. Silvers:-</salute>
				</opener>
				<p>
					The military address of Graham Pelton, Ex '18,
					has been changed from <choice><abbr>Co.</abbr><expan>Company</expan></choice> "E", 1st Replacement Regiment of Engrs.,
					to Room 205, Engineer School, Washington Barracks, D.C.
				</p>
				<p>
					Should like very much to receive your War Letters
					as heretofore.
				</p>

				<closer>
					<salute>Very truly yours,</salute><lb/>
					<signed>Graham Pelton</signed>
				</closer>
			</div>
